  "notes": [
    {
      "id": "ffc16f45-6887-ef11-8474-000d3a37e3b6",
      "type": "GeneralTitle",
      "area": "General",
      "position": 0,
      "content": "IMPORTANT MAJOR INFORMATION",
      "contentHtml": null
    },
    {
      "id": "f4c16f45-6887-ef11-8474-000d3a37e3b6",
      "type": "GeneralText",
      "area": "General",
      "position": 1,
      "content": "The Spanish and Community and Culture major combines hands-on learning experiences with the study of the language, linguistics, literature, and cultures of the Hispanic-heritage communities of Los Angeles and the United States. In real-world settings, students learn how the Spanish language can be used as a tool to better serve the communities, both local and global, that claim it as their primary means of communication. Listed below are the lower division preparation courses for the major. To be considered for this major, you must complete the following courses by the end of spring before transfer: One year of college level Spanish OR At least one year of high school in which the primary language of instruction was Spanish. Completion of two years of college level foreign language is STRONGLY RECOMMENDED . A placement exam is required for all language majors regardless of credits earned in lower division language courses. All courses must be taken for a letter grade. For more information regarding this major and UCLA's transfer selection process, visit https://spanport.ucla.edu and https:// admission.ucla.edu . PLEASE NOTE: the community college courses listed below have been approved to satisfy the preparation for this major at UCLA, but they may not be exact equivalents of the UCLA courses listed. In addition some language courses may be cross listed and available in different departments, however all major preparation courses must be taken from the Spanish department.",
      "contentHtml": "<p>The Spanish and Community and Culture major combines hands-on learning experiences with the study of the language, linguistics, literature, and cultures of the Hispanic-heritage communities of Los Angeles and the United States. In real-world settings, students learn how the Spanish language can be used as a tool to better serve the communities, both local and global, that claim it as their primary means of communication.</p><p><br></p><p>Listed below are the lower division preparation courses for the major.</p><p><br></p><p>To be considered for this major, you must complete the following courses by the end of spring before transfer:</p><ul><li>One year of college level Spanish OR</li><li>At least one year of high school in which the primary language of instruction was Spanish.</li></ul><p>Completion of two years of college level foreign language is <strong>STRONGLY RECOMMENDED</strong>. </p><p>A placement exam is required for all language majors regardless of credits earned in lower division language courses.</p><p>All courses must be taken for a letter grade.</p><p><br></p><p>For more information regarding this major and UCLA's transfer selection process, visit <u style=\"color: rgb(41, 98, 255);\">https://spanport.ucla.edu</u> and <u style=\"color: rgb(41, 98, 255);\">https://</u><a href=\"http://www.admission.ucla.edu\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">admission.ucla.edu</a>.</p><p><br></p><p>PLEASE NOTE: the community college courses listed below have been approved to satisfy the preparation for this major at UCLA, but they may not be exact equivalents of the UCLA courses listed. In addition some language courses may be cross listed and available in different departments, however all major preparation courses must be taken from the Spanish department.</p>"
    }
